  "topic_name": "Metals and Non-Metals",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Elements are classified into metals and non-metals based on their properties. Metals are lustrous (shiny), malleable (can be beaten into sheets), ductile (can be drawn into wires), and good conductors of heat and electricity. Examples include iron, copper, gold, and silver. Non-metals are generally dull, brittle, and poor conductors. Examples include carbon, sulfur, and oxygen. There are some exceptions: mercury is a liquid metal, graphite (a form of carbon) conducts electricity. Metals react with oxygen to form metal oxides, with water to form hydroxides, and with acids to form salts and hydrogen gas.",
    "rules": [
      "Metals are lustrous (shiny)",
      "Metals are malleable (can be beaten into sheets)",
      "Metals are ductile (can be drawn into wires)",
      "Metals are good conductors of heat and electricity",
      "Non-metals are generally dull and brittle",
      "Non-metals are poor conductors of heat and electricity",
      "Exception: Mercury is a liquid metal",
      "Exception: Graphite (non-metal) conducts electricity",
      "Metals react with oxygen to form metal oxides",
      "Metals react with acids to form salt and hydrogen"
    ]
  },
